          "en": "Why Fabric Shrinkage Happens — And Why Professional Pre-Shrinking Matters in Streetwear Manufacturing"
        },
        "content": {
          "zh": "Introduction://\nFabric shrinkage is one of the most common quality issues in garment manufacturing, especially in heavyweight streetwear production. Hoodies becoming shorter after washing, T-shirts twisting after drying, or inconsistent sizing across production batches are all direct results of uncontrolled fabric shrinkage.//\nFor modern apparel brands, shrinkage control is no longer just a fabric issue — it directly affects garment fit, customer satisfaction, return rates, and long-term brand reputation.//\nAt Kellogg, fabric shrinkage testing and pre-shrinking control are critical parts of our manufacturing process, particularly for oversized silhouettes, heavyweight cotton fabrics, and garment-washed streetwear collections.//\nWhat Causes Fabric Shrinkage:Fabric shrinkage occurs when textile fibers release internal tension during washing, drying, or heat exposure.During knitting, weaving, dyeing, and finishing processes, fabrics are placed under mechanical tension. Once exposed to water and heat, the fibers naturally attempt to return to a more relaxed state, resulting in dimensional changes.//\nSeveral major factors contribute to shrinkage://\n1. Fiber Composition:Natural fibers such as cotton are significantly more prone to shrinkage than synthetic fibers.Cotton fibers absorb water easily, causing the yarn structure to swell and contract during washing. This is especially noticeable in heavyweight cotton fleece and French terry fabrics commonly used in premium streetwear garments.Polyester fabrics generally have better dimensional stability because synthetic fibers are heat-set during production.//\n\n2. Fabric Construction:Knitted fabrics shrink more easily than woven fabrics because knitted loops have greater elasticity and movement.This is why oversized T-shirts, hoodies, sweatpants, and relaxed-fit garments require more advanced shrinkage control compared to structured woven products.Heavy GSM fabrics also create additional internal tension, increasing the risk of post-wash shrinkage.//\n\n3. Dyeing and Washing Processes:Reactive dyeing, garment dyeing, enzyme washing, acid washing, and vintage washing can all alter fabric tension.Aggressive washing techniques may create://\nLength shrinkage //\nWidth shrinkage //\nTwisting //\nSeam distortion //\nUneven garment shape //\nFor streetwear brands pursuing washed or vintage aesthetics, shrinkage management becomes even more critical. //\nWhich Fabrics Should Use Washing Instead of Traditional Pre-Shrinking:Not all fabrics should rely only on mechanical pre-shrinking.Some specialty fabrics require controlled washing processes instead：//\nVintage Washed Fabrics:For vintage streetwear collections, garment washing is part of the intended visual aesthetic.Enzyme wash, stone wash, and pigment wash treatments help stabilize the fabric while simultaneously creating softness and faded effects.In these cases, washing becomes part of the dimensional stabilization process.//\nGarment Dyed Products:Garment dye garments typically undergo dyeing after sewing.Traditional pre-shrinking alone cannot fully predict final shrinkage because the garment experiences additional heat and moisture during dyeing.Therefore, wash testing after dyeing is critical.//\nAcid Wash and Snow Wash Fabrics:Aggressive wash treatments dramatically affect fiber tension and garment shape.Professional manufacturers usually combine://\nFabric relaxation //\nPre-tsting //\nWashtrials //\nPattern compensation //\nFinalQC measurement //",
          "en": "Introduction://\nFabric shrinkage is one of the most common quality issues in garment manufacturing, especially in heavyweight streetwear production. Hoodies becoming shorter after washing, T-shirts twisting after drying, or inconsistent sizing across production batches are all direct results of uncontrolled fabric shrinkage.//\nFor modern apparel brands, shrinkage control is no longer just a fabric issue — it directly affects garment fit, customer satisfaction, return rates, and long-term brand reputation.//\nAt Kellogg, fabric shrinkage testing and pre-shrinking control are critical parts of our manufacturing process, particularly for oversized silhouettes, heavyweight cotton fabrics, and garment-washed streetwear collections.//\nWhat Causes Fabric Shrinkage:Fabric shrinkage occurs when textile fibers release internal tension during washing, drying, or heat exposure.During knitting, weaving, dyeing, and finishing processes, fabrics are placed under mechanical tension. Once exposed to water and heat, the fibers naturally attempt to return to a more relaxed state, resulting in dimensional changes.//\nSeveral major factors contribute to shrinkage://\n1. Fiber Composition:Natural fibers such as cotton are significantly more prone to shrinkage than synthetic fibers.Cotton fibers absorb water easily, causing the yarn structure to swell and contract during washing. This is especially noticeable in heavyweight cotton fleece and French terry fabrics commonly used in premium streetwear garments.Polyester fabrics generally have better dimensional stability because synthetic fibers are heat-set during production.//\n\n2. Fabric Construction:Knitted fabrics shrink more easily than woven fabrics because knitted loops have greater elasticity and movement.This is why oversized T-shirts, hoodies, sweatpants, and relaxed-fit garments require more advanced shrinkage control compared to structured woven products.Heavy GSM fabrics also create additional internal tension, increasing the risk of post-wash shrinkage.//\n\n3. Dyeing and Washing Processes:Reactive dyeing, garment dyeing, enzyme washing, acid washing, and vintage washing can all alter fabric tension.Aggressive washing techniques may create://\nLength shrinkage //\nWidth shrinkage //\nTwisting //\nSeam distortion //\nUneven garment shape //\nFor streetwear brands pursuing washed or vintage aesthetics, shrinkage management becomes even more critical. //\nWhich Fabrics Should Use Washing Instead of Traditional Pre-Shrinking:Not all fabrics should rely only on mechanical pre-shrinking.Some specialty fabrics require controlled washing processes instead：//\nVintage Washed Fabrics:For vintage streetwear collections, garment washing is part of the intended visual aesthetic.Enzyme wash, stone wash, and pigment wash treatments help stabilize the fabric while simultaneously creating softness and faded effects.In these cases, washing becomes part of the dimensional stabilization process.//\nGarment Dyed Products:Garment dye garments typically undergo dyeing after sewing.Traditional pre-shrinking alone cannot fully predict final shrinkage because the garment experiences additional heat and moisture during dyeing.Therefore, wash testing after dyeing is critical.//\nAcid Wash and Snow Wash Fabrics:Aggressive wash treatments dramatically affect fiber tension and garment shape.Professional manufacturers usually combine://\nFabric relaxation //\nPre-tsting //\nWashtrials //\nPattern compensation //\nFinalQC measurement //"
